  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Bureaucracy</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Italian government processes are slow and paperwork-heavy. Budget extra time for everything. Offices close unexpectedly. Patience is mandatory.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Document Translation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">All documents must be translated into Italian by sworn translators. English documents will be rejected. Factor in translation time and costs.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing the 8-Day Registration</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must apply for your permesso di soggiorno within 8 days of arrival. Miss this deadline and you'll face complications.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Insufficient Insurance Coverage</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Travel insurance or basic policies may be rejected. Get comprehensive health insurance that clearly covers all medical needs.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">No Accommodation Proof</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Italy requires proof of housing. A signed lease or rental agreement is essential—Airbnb confirmations may not suffice.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring Regional Differences</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Consulate requirements and Questura procedures vary by location. What works in Milan may not work in Naples. Research your specific region.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Italy -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Italy</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Italy has excellent healthcare, ranked among the world's best by WHO. However, quality varies significantly between north and south, and digital nomads must rely on private care.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Private Healthcare Options</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Humanitas (Milan):</strong> World-class private hospital, fully English-speaking</li>
      <li><strong>Ospedale San Raffaele (Milan):</strong> Top research hospital with international patients unit</li>
      <li><strong>Rome American Hospital:</strong> Expat-friendly, American-style care</li>
      <li><strong>Salvator Mundi (Rome):</strong> Private hospital with English services</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Regional Quality Variation</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Northern Italy (Lombardy, Emilia-Romagna, Veneto) has excellent healthcare infrastructure. Southern regions, while improving, may have longer waits and fewer English-speaking providers.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Sample Costs (Without Insurance)</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Private GP visit:</strong> €80-150</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist consultation:</strong> €150-300</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency room (private):</strong> €200-500</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital stay per day:</strong> €500-1,500</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work for Italian clients on the Digital Nomad Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. The visa specifically requires that you work for clients or employers outside Italy. Working for Italian companies would require a different permit.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about the 7% flat tax I've heard about?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Italy offers a 7% flat tax on foreign income for new residents who relocate to certain southern regions (like Sicily, Sardinia, Calabria). Consult an Italian tax advisor to see if you qualify.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I travel throughout Schengen?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Italy is a Schengen member. Your DN visa allows travel throughout the 27-country Schengen zone for up to 90 days in other countries.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Italian?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not for the visa, but practically speaking, Italian proficiency makes life significantly easier. Outside tourist areas, English is limited. Government offices especially require Italian.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I bring my family?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, family members can apply for dependent visas. They'll need to prove the family relationship and may have additional insurance requirements.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is the visa renewable?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. The digital nomad visa can be renewed, typically for another year, provided you continue to meet the requirements. Apply for renewal before your current permit expires.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

